<% layout("./layouts/boilerplate") %>
  <h1>Inline and External Events</h1>
  <h2>Inline Events</h2>
  <p>
    We can have code run at specific events, like when the user clicks on a
    button:
  </p>
  <img src="onClick.png" alt="" />
  <p>(IN HTML)</p>
  <p>We need to pay attention to the quotes we use with inline events.</p>
  <div id="buttonDiv"><button class="btn btn-outline-success" onclick="alert('Hi')">Click Me!</button></div>
  <p>
    One downside with this method od events is that we need to type the same
    code every time we want that event to happen.
  </p>
  <p>
    Also, to have multiple events for the same action, we need to separate the
    events with a semicolon.
  </p>
  <img src="dblclick.png" alt="" />
  <div id="buttonDiv">
    <button class="btn btn-outline-success"
      ondblclick="alert('Why did you double-click me?');alert('DonÂ´t do it again!')">
      Double-click Me!
    </button>
  </div>
  <h2>External Events</h2>
  <p>
    We can also link our JS document to our HTML and create our events there.
    We normally use functions, which can be saved and used, or just created as
    function expressions. We must declare a variable to associate the event to
    our button.
  </p>
  <img src="externalEventsonclickHTML.png" alt="" />
  <p>Here we use a function expression:</p>
  <img src="externalEventsonclickJS.png" alt="" />
  <p></p>
  <div id="buttonDiv"><button class="btn btn-outline-success" id="btn1">Another button</button></div>
  <hr />
  <p>Here we declare a function, and save it to an event for our button:</p>
  <img src="onmouseenter.png" alt="" />
  <p>(It has a class of btn2 on our HTML)</p>
  <div id="buttonDiv"><button class="btn2 btn btn-outline-success">Please don't hover me!</button></div>
  <script src="inlineAndExternalEvents.js"></script>